HASE 3: Visualization & UI (Sub-agent: frontend)
Build a single-page React app (or vanilla HTML/JS if simpler for GitHub Pages) with the following views. Design should be clean, premium, light background — use the color palette from our pitch slides: warm off-white (#F7F5F0) background, deep navy (#1B2A4A) for headings, burnt orange (#D4532D) for problem/risk indicators, deep teal (#2A7F62) for solutions/positive metrics, warm gold (#C49A2A) for data/neutral elements.
Navigation: Top nav or sidebar with 6 views.
View 1 — Territory Overview (landing page)

Map of Hyderabad with 500 outlet pins, color-coded by health (green = healthy, amber = at-risk, red = probable stockout). Use Leaflet.js or a simple SVG map.
Summary cards at top: Total outlets, Total revenue (trailing 30d), Stockout events detected, Revenue at risk, Average forecast accuracy.
Clicking an outlet opens a detail panel (View 5).

View 2 — Stockout Heatmap

Matrix view: rows = top 20 SKUs, columns = beats (or pin codes). Cell color = stockout frequency (white → amber → red).
Filters: time range (last 4 weeks / 12 weeks / 52 weeks), channel type, archetype.
Below the matrix: "Revenue at risk" rollup — big number, broken down by SKU. This is the deliverable we promised. Make it feel like a finding, not a dashboard.
Key insight callout box: "Dairy Milk Silk has the highest stockout rate (12%) concentrated in 3 beats — ₹X lakhs/month at risk."

View 3 — Outlet Archetypes

Visual cluster map (scatter plot or grouped cards) showing the 5-6 archetypes with outlet count, avg revenue, defining characteristics.
Click into an archetype to see its ideal basket and the outlets assigned to it.
This is the "outlet archetype map" deliverable.

View 4 — Smart Basket

Outlet selector (search/dropdown). Shows selected outlet's current ordering pattern (last 8 weeks avg) side by side with the AI-recommended basket.
Visual diff: green bars for "add this SKU," red bars for "you're over-ordering this," gray for "on track."
Estimated monthly uplift in ₹ if recommendations are adopted.
This is the "per-store basket engine" deliverable.

View 5 — Outlet Detail (drill-down)

Selected outlet's profile: name, pin code, channel, beat, archetype assignment.
Time series chart: actual sales vs. forecast for each SKU over 52 weeks. Highlight stockout events as red dots.
Mini basket comparison (same as View 4 but inline).

View 6 — Pilot Simulation (Lift vs. Control)

Side-by-side comparison: test group (250 outlets with smart basket) vs. control group (250 outlets, status quo).
Line chart: cumulative secondary sales over 90 days, diverging.
Summary: "Test group showed X% lift in secondary sales, ₹Y lakhs incremental revenue over 90 days."
"Scale / no-scale" recommendation box with bullet rationale.
This is the "lift vs. control" and "scale / no-scale memo" deliverable.

Global UI elements:

Every view should have a small disclaimer footer: "Prototype — synthetic data for demonstration purposes"
Mondelez brand names should appear naturally (Dairy Milk, Silk, 5 Star etc.) — this is their data, not ours.
Numbers should use Indian formatting (₹, lakhs, crores).
The prototype should feel like you're looking at a real analytics tool, not a mockup. Interactive filters, hover tooltips, clickable drill-downs.
